# Prefer Trunk for Linting

Always use `trunk check` for linting instead of invoking linters directly.

## Commands

```bash
# ✅ GOOD - Use trunk
trunk check --fix
trunk check --filter eslint
trunk check --filter eslint --fix

# ❌ BAD - Don't invoke linters directly
npx eslint .
eslint --fix .
prettier --check .
```

## Why Trunk?

- Consistent linting configuration across all tools
- Avoids confirmation prompts when using `--fix`
- Unified output format
- Respects project's `.trunk/trunk.yaml` configuration

## trunk check vs trunk fmt

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `trunk check --fix` | Run all linters and auto-fix issues (linting + formatting) |
| `trunk fmt` | Run only formatters (faster, formatting only) |

**When to use `trunk fmt`:**
- Quick formatting before commits
- When you only need to fix whitespace/formatting issues
- Faster than full `trunk check` when you don't need linting

**When to use `trunk check --fix`:**
- After making code changes that may introduce lint errors
- Before opening a PR
- When you need both linting and formatting fixes

## Common Patterns

| Instead of | Use |
|------------|-----|
| `npx eslint .` | `trunk check --filter eslint` |
| `npx eslint --fix .` | `trunk check --filter eslint --fix` |
| `npx prettier --check .` | `trunk check --filter prettier` |
| `npx prettier --write .` | `trunk fmt` or `trunk check --filter prettier --fix` |
